            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Daniel Kaplan\u2019s understanding of San Francisco was forged not in its gleaming tech towers, but in the fragrant steam of his mother\u2019s Daly City cafe. The son of a first-generation Korean immigrant and a Jewish-American high school history teacher, Daniel grew up navigating a world of kimchi and kugel, fluent in the languages of both fierce entrepreneurial spirit and civic history. His childhood was a comfortable, hardworking Bay Area existence, defined by the clatter of dishes and dinner-table debates about public policy.\n\nThe 2008 financial crisis was the turning point. He was a teenager when he watched his mother struggle, poring over bewildering loan applications and city regulations just to keep her cafe afloat. It was then that the abstract lessons from his father\u2019s history class became intensely personal. He saw how policy, written in distant offices, had a direct and often painful impact on the lives of people he loved. This ignited a quiet but fierce determination to understand and change the system from within.\n\nHe pursued a Public Policy degree at UC Berkeley, where his passion for local governance crystallized. While his peers were lured by Silicon Valley, Daniel interned at City Hall. Upon graduating, he secured a coveted position as a Legislative Aide. Now, at 25, his life is a blur of policy briefings, constituent emails, and community meetings.\n\nHis 3.8-mile commute on the N Judah from his shared Inner Richmond apartment is his time to decompress, observing the city he works to serve. Life on an $82,000 salary means roommates and budgeting, but he feels rich in purpose. He lives and breathes San Francisco, from grabbing dim sum on Clement Street to weekend hikes in the Presidio with his long-term girlfriend, Maya, a non-profit advocate he met at Cal.\n\nDaniel\u2019s ambition extends far beyond his current role. He views his job as an apprenticeship. He harbors a well-guarded dream of one day running for District Supervisor, to be the one crafting legislation that protects small business owners like his mother and ensures the city remains accessible for everyone. For Daniel, public service isn't a career; it\u2019s a promise he made to his family long ago."
